# WARG Embedded Hardware/Software Bootcamp

**Introduction:**

WARG members often find that joining this team requires more knowledge and has a larger learning curve than other student teams. Once members have acquired this knowledge they gain a lot of confidence and are able to make large contributions to the team. Therefore, this Bootcamp is designed as a first task to be completed to both help you through the learning curve, while giving you a project that is fully your own. The hope is that once you complete this Bootcamp you will feel confident and hopefully have acquired enough skills such that you are ready to take on tasks with our aircraft! Just a quick disclaimer, this Bootcamp will help accelerate and minimize the learning curve but it will not give you all knowledge. The remaining knowledge will be acquired through completing other tasks with the team.

**Bootcamp Objectives:**

·         Learn to program using Embedded C (most common language for microcontrollers)

·         Learn common programming conventions and tricks

·         Begin understanding how software works on a hardware level

·         Make a car maneuver and allow it to communicate with the GPS

·         Learn basic computer-aided circuit design principles.

·         Learn how to make a PCB board.

**Bootcamp Outline:**

This Bootcamp has two options, both of which require a Team Leads approval of completion in order to move onto working on other tasks. The estimated time of completion for this bootcamp is approximately ~5 hours.



**1.**   **R/C Car Automation and GPS Circuit Design**

**Background:** R/C cars are a great way to simulate a flying plane. Aerial vehicles are easy to crash, however the R/C cars only operate in two dimension. It is easier to program an R/C car in comparison to a fixed-wing aircraft or quadcopter. Nonetheless, the electronics onboard are very similar to the PicPilot (the name of our Autopilot). In essence, the code running on the R/C car is a reduced version of the code that controls the plane.

GPS devices are one of the most critical components of our system. It provides us with longitude and latitude information, time, speed and heading. The GPS unit on our aircraft allows it to follow a path, autonomously.

GPS devices use a standard called NMEA sentences. This standard _string data_ to transmit information. It is a very inefficient form of data transfer. This is an example of an NMEA string:

_$GPRMC,183729,A,3907.356,N,12102.482,W,000.0,360.0,080301,015.5,E\*6F_

This sentence transmits the corresponding data. Each character about requires one byte (8 bits) of data. This is inefficient, and it makes it difficult to do math on the data in the NMEA string. As a result, a conversion microcontroller is used, whose sole purpose is to convert the NMEA string into a useable format to transmit to other devices.

Although any microcontroller can be used, the PIC24F16KA101 because it is small, inexpensive, and very power efficient.

**Task:**

You can do it in any order. If there are a lot of people waiting to test the R/C car. Try to complete Part 2.

Part 1 - R/C Car Automation

The task is fairly straightforward. You must drive the car at a moderate speed (not too fast) for 3 seconds going straight. After 3 seconds, you must turn 90° right. For another 3 seconds, drive straight. After 6 seconds, you must turn 90° right again. For another 3 seconds, drive straight. After 9 seconds, you must turn 90° right again. For another 3 seconds, drive straight. After 12 seconds, you must turn 90° right again. You should be very close to your starting position.

Essentially, you must program the car to drive a square path:

**The functions available on the R/C Car include:**

setSteering(int percent);

This function does exactly what you think it does. It takes an int value input ranging from -100 to 100.    With -100 turning the wheels fully to the left, and 100 turning the wheels fully to the right.

setThrottle(int percent);

This function does exactly what you think it does. It takes an int value input ranging from -100 to 100. With -100 being full speed in reverse, and 100 being full speed forward.

getTime();

This function returns the time in milliseconds as type _long int_, the function takes no inputs.

See the R/C Car Help Document for more info and detailed explanations.

Part 2 - GPS Design Interfacing

This task is a little bit more complicated than the first task. It requires being able to design a circuit board. At the minimum, you should be able to create a schematic which can interface the PicPilot. To fully complete this task, you must create a PCB design, the best designed one will be sent to get fabricated and will be used during Unmanned Systems Canada Competition.

This task may be completed in either [Diptrace](http://diptrace.com/download-diptrace/#DownloadForm/1/) (download freeware) or [EagleCAD](http://www.cadsoftusa.com/download-eagle/) (download).

You will need to look at the [GPS datasheet](https://www.adafruit.com/datasheets/GlobalTop-FGPMMOPA6H-Datasheet-V0A.pdf) for how to design the circuit and the [PIC24F16KA101 datasheet](http://ww1.microchip.com/downloads/en/DeviceDoc/39927c.pdf). The datasheet contains all the specifications, and pins on how to connect the circuit.

The GPS communicates via a UART connection. UART stands for Universal Asynchronous Receive Transmit. It is a serial form of communication. A good description of what it is and how it works can be found here: [http://docs.uwarg.com/picpilot/uart/](http://docs.uwarg.com/picpilot/uart/)

The PIC24F16KA101 must read the UART data. In the code it will convert the data into a useable format for the aircraft PicPilot to understand (don't worry you don't have to know the details). The data is then output via SPI.

SPI stands for Serial Peripheral Interface. It is also a form of serial communication. A good description of what it is and how it works can be found here:

[http://docs.uwarg.com/picpilot/spi/](http://docs.uwarg.com/picpilot/spi/)

If you need help with using the CAD software, diptrace tutorials can be found here:

Schematics: [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uCPUqXFvUZU](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uCPUqXFvUZU)

PCB Layout: [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kw51rlCTYBY](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kw51rlCTYBY)

PDF Tutorial: [http://www.diptrace.com/books/tutorial.pdf](http://www.diptrace.com/books/tutorial.pdf)
